Great observation! Let me explain why we write **1 ≤ x < 5** and not **1 ≤ x ≤ 5**.

---

## The Rule of Boundary Points

Each critical point **belongs to exactly ONE case** — we can't have it in two cases at the same time!

---

## Think of it like rooms in a house 🏠

```
←————————•————————————•————————→
        x=1          x=5

  Room 1  | Room 2      | Room 3
  x < 1   | 1 ≤ x < 5  | x ≥ 5
```

> x=1 belongs to Room 2 (left boundary)
> x=5 belongs to Room 3 (left boundary)

**Every point must be in exactly ONE room!**

---

## What actually happens AT x=5?

```
At x=5:
|x-5| = |5-5| = 0
```

Zero is **neither positive nor negative!**

So at x=5 exactly, the expression (x-5) = 0, which means it doesn't matter whether we write + or − because:

```
+(5-5) = 0
-(5-5) = 0
```
**Both give the same answer!** So x=5 is assigned to Case 3 by convention.

---

## Visual Proof

```
Case 2 ends:        Case 3 starts:
x approaches 5      x = 5 exactly
    ↓                    ↓
←———•————————————[→•←]————————→
   x=1          x=5

        NO GAP!
        NO OVERLAP!
```

---

## The Pattern Always Follows This 🔑

```
Case 1:  x < 1        (open at 1)
Case 2:  1 ≤ x < 5    (closed at 1, open at 5)
Case 3:  x ≥ 5        (closed at 5)
```

Each **opening bracket** of one case matches the **closing bracket** of the previous!

---

## Simple Way to Remember

| Point | Excluded from LEFT case | Included in RIGHT case |
|-------|------------------------|----------------------|
| x=1 | Case 1 (x<1) | Case 2 (x≥1) |
| x=5 | Case 2 (x<5) | Case 3 (x≥5) |

> Think of it as: **each critical point starts a new case!** 🎯


